<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Flicker" class="currentChild" href="Flicker">Flicker</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A perceptible fluctuation in the intensity of a computer monitor's display produced during <a title="Refresh" href="Refresh">refresh</a> cycles when the <a title="Refresh Rate" href="Refresh_Rate">refresh rate</a> exceeds the persistance of the phosphors coating the back of the screen. Flicker is also observed in a television or video picture when the two <a title="Field" href="Field">field</a>s of a particular <a title="Frame" href="Frame">frame</a> are not properly synchronized. A particular type of flicker—called <a title="Interlace Flicker" href="Interlace_Flicker">interlace flicker</a>—is a condition that affects monitors whose image is formed by means of <a title="Interlacing" href="Interlacing">interlacing</a>. See <a title="Interlacing" href="Interlacing">Interlacing</a> and <a title="Interlace Flicker" href="Interlace_Flicker">Interlace Flicker</a>. 
</p>
